JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1803
EP  - 1840
VL  - 91
IS  - 5
KW  - Credit scores
KW  - unsecured consumer credit
KW  - bankruptcy
KW  - persistent hidden information
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA18771
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - What is the role of credit scores in credit markets? We argue that it is, in part, the market's assessment of a person's unobservable type, which here we take to be patience. We postulate a model of persistent hidden types where observable actions shape the public assessment of a person's type via Bayesian updating. We show how dynamic reputation can incentivize repayment. Importantly, we show how an economy with credit scores implements the same equilibrium allocation. We estimate the model using both credit market data and the evolution of individuals' credit scores. We conduct counterfactuals to assess how more or less information used in scoring individuals affects outcomes and welfare. If tracking of individual credit actions is outlawed, poor young adults of low type benefit from subsidization by high types despite facing higher interest rates arising from lower dynamic incentives to repay.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Platform Design When Sellers Use Pricing Algorithms
AU  - Johnson, Justin P.
AU  - Rhodes, Andrew
AU  - Wildenbeest, Matthijs
Y1  - 2023/09/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA19978
